<h2><a name='sect0' href='#toc0'>Name</a></h2>

<p> shmem_barrier_all - Suspends the execution of the calling PE until
all other PEs issue a call to this particular shmem_barrier_all() statement.

<h2><a name='sect1' href='#toc1'>Synopsis</a></h2>

<p> C or C++: <br>
<pre>#include &lt;mpp/shmem.h&gt;
void shmem_barrier_all(void);
</pre> Fortran: <br>
<pre>include &rsquo;mpp/shmem.h&rsquo;
CALL SHMEM_BARRIER_ALL
</pre>
<h2><a name='sect2' href='#toc2'>Description</a></h2>

<p> The shmem_barrier_all routine does not return until all other
PEs have entered this routine at the same point of the execution path. <p>
Prior
to synchronizing with other PEs, shmem_barrier_all ensures completion of
all previously issued local memory stores and remote memory updates issued
via SHMEM functions such as <i><i>shmem_put32</i>(3)</i>. <p>

<h2><a name='sect3' href='#toc3'>Examples</a></h2>

<p> <br>
<pre>setup_data()
{
  if (shmem_my_pe() == 0) {
    setup();
  }
  /* All PEs wait for PE 0 to complete setup().  */
  shmem_barrier_all();
}
</pre> <p>

<h2><a name='sect4' href='#toc4'>See Also</a></h2>

